 Zip drive 			 
				 From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia 				 
								 
					Jump to:					 navigation , 					 search 
				 
				 This article is about the drive that reads and writes Zip floppy disks. For the ZIP archive file format, see  Zip (file format) . 
 
 
 
 
Iomega ZIP-100 drive logo 
 
 
 
 
 
 
External ZIP-100 drive (available in parallel port and  SCSI  versions) 
 
 
 
 
 
 
An internal Zip drive installed in a computer 
 
 
 
 
 
 
An internal Zip drive outside of a computer but attached to a 3.5-inch to 5.25-inch drive bay adapter 
 
 
 
 
 
 
The Zip disk media 
 
 
 
 
 
 
Back of the ZIP-100 with parallel port printer pass-through 
 
 
 The  Zip drive  is a medium-to-high-capacity (at the time of its release) removable floppy  disk storage  system that was introduced by  Iomega  in late 1994. Originally, Zip disks launched with capacities of 100  MB , but later versions increased this to first 250 MB and then 750 MB. 
